segments.text: have you seen or have you noticed a difference in the role of women or the way women are treated between the north and the south?
I think that in a sense you may be talking I really
don't see the stereotype of the southern woman.
I see people filling the stereotype, that's not what I mean.
But I don't feel, I think the southern woman is just as strong as the northern woman.
And I think she may role play a little bit more and may seem more feminine
But there are lots of very feminine women in the North, too.
I think you can build up stereotypes until really they're meaningless.
But I went to school in the 50s in North Carolina.
I knew a lot of Southern women.
And most of them were hell on wheels.
I mean, they were super intelligent.
They were manipulative.
Many of them were full of leading families.
They knew how to juggle power.
They could be feminine.
I have a friend in Texas who is one of the most feminine women.
If you spoke to her, you would say, this is the personification of the stereotype of the Southern woman.
She is sweet.
She is sugary.
So on and so forth.
And I want you to know this woman can manipulate legislators in the field of mental health.
I mean, she can get people to do almost anything.
And she's super smart.
And she has a publication list as long as three arms.
And when my daughter first met her, she really didn't like her.
You see, because she took that stereotype.
But when she got to know her, it was a different matter.
And Dr. Merritt has been looking at ranch women.
And you get some of that role playing there, but on the other hand, these women are just super.
I mean, they fill men's roles, or they fill important roles.
This business of a man's role versus a woman's role.
I think some of these are stereotypes.
There are in every society women and men
who do not perform well.
Men as well as women.
And it depends on how you analyze this.
It's just like women who say women do derogatory tasks and men do all the important things.
A lot of nonsense.
You sit down and you figure out how many derogatory tasks men do
like carrying out garbage or so and so forth versus washing dishes.
I mean, whatever it is, there are always problems.
That kind of leads to my next question.
Well, you know, some people feel that marriage is a form of servitude and, you know, why women accept men, their husband's name, and that when they get married, they tend to lose their identity.
And, you know, how do you feel about this?
I think housework is a form of servitude anyway.
I mean, I don't enjoy housework.
And, I mean, I don't think it's anything profitable.
It's like going to search out bibliography using a car file and index when you can do it on the computer.
You know, it's a waste of time.
If there's an easier way of doing it, do it.
There are certain things I like.
I like to cook if I didn't gain weight.
And I like to sew.
I mean, just because it's different from what I do every day.
So there are lots of things I like to do, but I think housework is drudgery.
And unless it's something you like to do as a hobby or to do something different from your everyday work,
everybody has to do it until we have robots or something that will do all these tasks, both male and female.
I mean, if you're living in a house, somebody's got to keep it clean and somebody has to cook the meals unless you can afford to eat every meal out.
Somebody's got to do it.
And if it's a male living in a house, the male has to do it.
If it's a female living in a house... Now, there are people who have had...
who do not have a husband or a wife who will do these things.
In other words, there are women who say, my husband will not lift a finger in the house.
And I think that is very hard.
I happen to have a husband who has always been willing to help.
And if one of us has special work, then the other one tries to free the other one.
And almost everybody that we knew who were in school with us
did the same thing.
And large numbers of working families share the work.
But my father always did things.
He didn't clean, but he would do the dishes.
And in some ways, my mother is a really good cook, but in some ways there were things that my father could cook better.
Not that he...
that he rushed around doing it.
But mother never had to carry out the garbage.
She never had to do all the, never had to worry about house repair or any of those things.
I mean, it was a sharing of responsibility.
I think sometimes after a while you get awfully tired of some of these things and you think, well, I need help.
But you really have to assess how much the other person does.
I see.
And did you feel that when you got married and accepted your husband's name,
that you lost some of your identity or your being a separate person?
No, but nobody was talking about that then.
Maybe I would have if everybody had been talking about it.
But what's in a name, really?
And I know that younger faculty members feel differently about this.
But what's so precious about your father's name versus your husband?
I mean, in our society, names come down through the male line.
In some societies, they come down through the female line.
I'm not sure that this makes you a better person or makes you less of an individual.
I mean, Margaret Mead would have been Margaret Mead
whether she was a mead or whatever her maiden name was.
I just don't think...
I don't think the name...
I think you can put too much emphasis on these things and not put emphasis on getting your work done.
Do you feel that women today, and when you talk about the younger faculty, do you think that they put too much into these things?
I think there's a little bit too much...
I don't think you can interpret everything that happens to you as being male-female.
And I think when you do this, you're mishearing everything else that happens.
And you're always looking for someone who is discriminating against you.
And I just think it's a waste of time.

But I have, if I had been discriminated against seriously, I mean in an area that was especially important to me, if I had had work limitations or had felt that the resources in a particular department was such that I was not getting my share, maybe I would feel the same way.
You've got to look at the way a lot of men feel, too.
Because you can be in a department with all men, and half the men can feel that a department head or a corporate head is discriminating against them.
And what reason do you give?
Because they're male?
I mean, there are people, if you have an all-male division, there are going to be people who feel that they're being discriminated against.
What's the basis of that discrimination?
Talent?
Ability to sell yourself?
I believe in equality, but I think there are better ways of fighting for it than to keep dwelling on it.
For example, I'm not sure
how important women's studies are.
I don't think any area ought to be neglected.
But I really feel in education at this point in time, you ought to be educating people for jobs.
How do you educate people for jobs?
What are they going to do if they have a whole bunch of courses in women's studies?
Is everybody going to teach women's studies?
Or is everybody going into an agency that is going to guarantee civil rights of females?
I mean, what are you going to do with women's studies?
That's a good point.
Yeah, I mean, I can understand that if I were teaching a course in...
that fit into that category that I might want to fight for just because I might want to teach a course in that area.
But I think the bottom line is, what can you do with it?
Is it going to get you a job, meat on the table, new clothes, a house?
And I don't see it as being a profitable area.
Well, Dr. Shepherd, those are all the questions that I have for you.
Is there anything that you would like to add?
How do you feel about some of the things you've heard?
Well, I'm still trying to assess it all.
It's been very interesting to get a different point of view after interviewing Dr. Sell and you.
And I'm going to go on and try to interview Dr. Merritt.
And I think that will be just another person's point of view.
And I'm interested in this because I'm looking at a career in academia, in research, and being a professor.
And so I'm just kind of taking it all in, trying to make my own decisions.
Well, I think it's one of the easier fields for women to be in.
I think that if and when you marry, it's always helpful to marry somebody who is understanding.
But there are always, it doesn't matter whether you're married or you have a roommate or whatever the situation is,
If work demands a major proportion of your time and you're not able to juggle things so that you're not assuming responsibilities in the private sector of your life, there are always conflicts.
In other words, if you have a roommate and you don't keep your
your room clean or you don't do your share of the work, there's going to be conflict.
So there's going to be conflict anywhere.
Living together with people means that there's got to be a give and take.
And why one would expect that there wouldn't be, I don't know.
But it almost, some of...
of the expressed attitudes make it appear that women have the hardest row and men don't.
And I guess over the years, certainly since the development of the overt women's movement, a lot of young men, students at the university, have come to me and they have
they have raised questions about how they can handle their personal life.
They have met this girl and they really like her and she wants to have a career and if they had their way that would be okay up until the time they have children.
But you know that
The woman doesn't feel that way.
How do you handle this and not lose the girl?
I mean, essentially some of the same things that women are feeling.
You know, how much do you really tell someone you're thinking of marrying about the way you really feel?
And I guess, you know, the off-the-cuff answer is it's better to at least explain how you feel and talk about how you can work it out.
rather than role-playing and then getting into marriage and suddenly finding that you were married to this person who has very different views.
If you had discussed them and worked out some arrangement before marriage, it would be a lot easier.
But it's hard.
In any courtship situation, there's a lot of role-playing.
And it's hard to get by that.
A few years ago, when we began to get a lot of change, young people as well as old people living together, unmarried, and stuff like that, I had a secretary who worked for me on a research project.
And she was very outspoken.
Her husband was getting a doctorate in something like tree genetics.
And she had a little boy.
And a lot of the graduate students used to flock around her.
She was quite an interesting person and very, very talented.
I mean, she was way overqualified for secretary, so it was great for me.
And they would talk about some boy they were living with.
in town.
And she would say, you're all crazy.
She says, you're living with this person and you're doing his laundry and you're doing all these things and you're sitting around hoping that he'll marry you.
And she says, you don't get any of the perks that you get when you're courting.
Because he never takes you out
or take you out very seldom, never spends any money on you, no gifts.
And she was really quite interesting.
And I had a graduate student who very romantically met this boy in December, just before the, oh, I would say maybe three weeks from now.
And her car broke down, and he lived in her apartment area.
She'd never met him, and he helped her fix it.
And so she invited him to dinner.
And then they saw each other every day for about three weeks before he went out into, he was in banking, or he was going to be in banking.
And he had to serve an apprenticeship for a semester in his graduate program.
So he went out to California to do this, and she was madly in love with him.
And so he asked her to come and live with him for a month to see whether they could get along.
And so our secretary said, oh, you know, that's a lot of nonsense, you know, and so on and so forth.
And, uh, principally because she was afraid the girl would have her heart broken, you know.
And so she asked me what I thought, and, uh, and I said, well, I didn't think
It was such a hot idea.
But she went anyway.
And she went out there for three weeks.
She was working on her thesis at the time.
She went out there for three weeks.
She came back with a diamond the size of a cantaloupe.
Oh, my goodness.
And she had this big wedding.
I mean, and she's very happily married and has two children now.
So, you know, that was the last time I opened my mouth.
But they don't all happen like that.
Because a lot of them happen like the secretary said, that the girl is hoping the boy's going to marry her, and nothing happens.
Or the boy is hoping the girl will marry him, and she doesn't.
So interpersonal relationships are very difficult.
And they are complicated by changes, and not knowing how to change them, and not knowing how to communicate feelings.
Not to communicate them with this.
It's either going to be this way or not at all.
But to communicate them with, I care for you.
How can we work this out?
That kind, a more reasonable approach.
And I think we'll have problems for a while.
But I don't see any way in our society that females will be removed from the workforce
unless large numbers of jobs are removed.
In fact, there may be more females in the workforce than males if females are more technically oriented, more into the kinds of jobs that are going to be available in the next several years.
I mean, you look at the number of students in business
And I think they're over the 50% mark now in female.
That's interesting.
At least, someone told me that.
I don't remember whether it was Dawn Wood who told me that or not.
Somebody told me quite recently.
Well, I'll have to look into it and find out those statistics.
That would be very interesting.
But you see, in those fields, and the number of women engineers is increasing.
Well, thank you for your time.
You are very welcome.
